{
  "slug": "the-top-10-garbage-revenge-movies-and-rebel-ridge-with-jerem",
  "title": "The Top 10 Garbage Revenge Movies and ‘Rebel Ridge,’ With Jeremy Saulnier!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2024-09-10",
  "runtimeMin": 113,
  "format": "Sean and Chris Ryan use Jeremy Saulnier's 'Rebel Ridge' to define the eighth entry in their garbage series, garbage revenge, then talk through the vigilante canon from 'Point Blank' to 'John Wick.' Saulnier joins to talk civil forfeiture, a shoot that shut down three times across three years, and finding Aaron Pierre.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The festival dispatch",
      "note": "Venice, TIFF, and the fall slate",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Room Next Door",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Almodóvar's first English-language feature took the Golden Lion out of a Venice slate Sean calls mostly mediocre."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Brutalist",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Brady Corbett's 3.5-hour epic; A24 paid a reported $10M. Sean's most-anticipated of the fall: 'Sean porn,' per people who've seen it. Amanda is unconvinced."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A24's rollout went limited, then narrower instead of wide. Sean thinks it's been backburnered for 'The Brutalist.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "We Live in Time",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The Andrew Garfield / Florence Pugh drama, premiered at TIFF."
        },
        {
          "title": "Babygirl",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Nicole Kidman won Best Actress at Venice; a Best Actress play more than a Best Picture one."
        },
        {
          "title": "Queer",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Guadagnino's second 2024 film, with Daniel Craig; adapts Burroughs. Sounds like too much of a head trip for a serious awards push."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Chris's one lock in a genre-heavy year: the Best Picture slot the Academy needs for eyeballs."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nickel Boys",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Audacious enough that Sean thinks it may be too avant-garde for broad acceptance; Chris wants it and 'The Brutalist' to be the year's two poles, like Moonlight/La La Land."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nightbitch",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amy Adams as a mother turning feral. Sean thinks it's one of the worst trailers he's ever seen and won't watch unless obligated."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Life of Chuck",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Mike Flanagan's kinder, gentler Stephen King. Sean gets defensive when a film sells itself on the greatness of the human heart."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hard Truths",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Mike Leigh reuniting with Marianne Jean-Baptiste, ~30 years after 'Secrets & Lies.' A wide January release."
        },
        {
          "title": "Friendship",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Paul Rudd and Tim Robinson; Adam Nayman DM'd Sean from TIFF that it's incredibly funny."
        },
        {
          "title": "Emilia Pérez",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean doubts Chris will respond to the film but bets he'll love Zoe Saldaña."
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclave",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Ralph Fiennes, cited as one of the year's few clearly very good performances."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Piano Lesson",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Danielle Deadwyler, another performance Sean rates as very good but not a can't-believe-it sensation."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Rebel Ridge’",
      "note": "Saulnier's fourth feature, on Netflix",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Rebel Ridge",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Aaron Pierre plays Terry Richmond, an ex-Marine who confronts a corrupt Louisiana town after cops seize the cash he needs to bail out his cousin: a portrait of civil asset forfeiture built as 'First Blood meets Michael Clayton.' Visceral but restrained; nobody gets killed, just disarmed. Sean and Chris both around a 4/5, with the middle running long. Started with John Boyega, shut down mid-shoot, recast to Pierre."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Garbage revenge",
      "note": "the 8th in the garbage series: the lean, mean vigilante canon",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Point Blank",
          "year": 1967,
          "note": "John Boorman's New Hollywood opener; a Westlake/Parker adaptation. Chris's first all-timer, a crime-gone-wrong and one man getting after everybody. Borderline too classy."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rolling Thunder",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Written by Paul Schrader, a Vietnam vet on a revenge spree with William Devane. Somewhere between prestige and programmer, boosted by Tarantino's advocacy. You never think he'll be okay."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Limey",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "Soderbergh directing Terence Stamp: a genius downshifting to a gnarly programmer, which Sean calls his favorite thing in the world."
        },
        {
          "title": "John Wick",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "The first one specifically, for the very basic setup before the mythology. They pushed him too far and now it's on."
        },
        {
          "title": "Man on Fire",
          "year": 2004,
          "note": "Tony Scott and John Creasy: the patron saint of the modern genre, per Sean, even if Chris runs a little down on it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blue Ruin",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "Saulnier's breakout; the one Chris holds space for. A movie about the messiness and unsolvability of revenge."
        },
        {
          "title": "First Blood",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "Misremembered through its sequels: really a tragic story of a man with PTSD who just wants to be left alone. Saulnier's stated template for 'Rebel Ridge.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Falling Down",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "A '90s curio of samurai-like L.A. encounters; Sean pairs it with 'Rolling Thunder' as a film where you never think the guy will be okay. Chris files it more as societal-commentary travelogue."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wrath of Man",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Sean's recent-vintage sixth pick: Guy Ritchie in a 'Point Blank' job-gone-wrong groove, and the start of the Hartnett renaissance. He'd crown Statham a genre patron saint."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lady Vengeance",
          "year": 2005,
          "note": "Chris's Park Chan-wook pick, chosen over 'Oldboy' to be different, part of the Vengeance trilogy."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bullet to the Head",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Late-period Walter Hill with Stallone; Chris calls it incredibly stupid and incredibly good."
        },
        {
          "title": "Darkman",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "Sam Raimi's down-and-dirty not-quite-superhero revenge movie; an all-timer for Chris."
        },
        {
          "title": "Death Wish",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "The Charles Bronson text still used as shorthand: 'it's Death Wish, but…' Sean prefers the Eastwood revenge Westerns of the era."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Outlaw Josey Wales",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "Eastwood as a Confederate soldier avenging his family, closely aligned with the subgenre, per Chris."
        },
        {
          "title": "High Plains Drifter",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The other signature Eastwood Western the two put right in the pocket of garbage revenge."
        },
        {
          "title": "Unforgiven",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "Chris's example of revenge as an empty, hollow pursuit that destroys the avenger as much as the avenged."
        },
        {
          "title": "Oldboy",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "Cited as an international classic of the form, a rung above the garbage tier."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Equalizer 3",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Chris likes the third maybe more than the first two: a shadow 'Man on Fire' sequel and an unabashed program. 'It's for your dad.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Death Sentence",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "Early James Wan with Kevin Bacon; somewhere between atrocious and genuinely amazing."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ms. 45",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "Abel Ferrara's rape-revenge film, pretty effective, though the two argue rape revenge is a separate study from garbage revenge."
        },
        {
          "title": "I Spit on Your Grave",
          "year": 1978,
          "note": "Named as a canonical rape-revenge title in the genre they set aside."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lady Snowblood",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The Japanese rape-revenge classic, part of a decades-long tradition tapping a dark place in the psyche."
        },
        {
          "title": "Promising Young Woman",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "A recent riff on the long rape-revenge history."
        },
        {
          "title": "Deliverance",
          "year": 1972,
          "note": "Debated as rape revenge, but the revenge is one scene and the rest is survivalist. Chris has seen it five or six times; revisits 'Dueling Banjos.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Jackson County Jail",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "A deep cut Chris says is worth seeking out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hannie Caulder",
          "year": 1971,
          "note": "The rare Western rape-revenge movie, with Raquel Welch: a friend's recommendation Sean's yet to see."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Virgin Spring",
          "year": 1960,
          "note": "Bergman's revenge film, floated but not on either long list."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation: Jeremy Saulnier",
      "guest": "Jeremy Saulnier on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Rebel Ridge",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Conceived in 2018 as 'First Blood with a bit of Michael Clayton,' after Saulnier wanted a competent hero as a break from his brutal filmography. He found the civil-forfeiture premise infuriating enough to unite left and right behind Terry. Shot in Louisiana over three years and two more shutdowns; Netflix let him cast Aaron Pierre, whom he knew was Terry within minutes of a Zoom."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Thing",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "His last great thing: a pristine Carpenter print at the newly reopened Egyptian, which turned him into a print nerd. He brought his daughter and watched her face during the chest scene."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
